metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #106
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)

metadata.name: Intricate 4x4 #91
metadata.description:
'Intricated 4x4' was one of the projects that took me the longest to develop. With each WIP, I realized that I could improve some detail, some feature looking for more pleasant, democratic and varied aesthetic results.

This work consists of generating four sets of particles (ellipses or squares) that appear in the four corners of the screen, respecting the predefined margin limits. These sets move towards the center following an attenuated decrease in size thanks to the combination of logarithm and mapping of frameCount and the size variable. This simple trick ensures smoother and less aggressive movements, bringing the observer a sense of tranquility. 

Combining the use of different palettes with some movement conditionals - functions back() and go() - and a charming touch of shading and depth, 'Intricated 4x4' can be considered one of my favorite 
works and I hope it will be for you, after the mint.

Palletes carefully chosen =)

_______________________________
Variability of editions is ensured by:
* 8 background colors
* 13 palettes x 4 colors = 52 colors picked one by one with a lot of care
* possibility to have a fantastic BW version (rarity: 5%)
* possibility to repeat the same palette for both sets (rarity: 8%)
* possibility to have squares intead of circles (rarity: 25%)
* a wide range of Shapes number
* a well thought number of frames, proportional to the total frameCount to make things 'softer'

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
* Press [S] to save your .png file
* Press [P] to play/pause your animation anytime you like (this increase exponentially your possibilities, right!?)

_______________________________
Creator: Kukuti
May 2022

metadata.name: Traversal #35
metadata.description:
Traversal is the marriage of two simple geometric ideas: a set of somewhat unruly, intersecting diagonal shapes, and a minimally reduced corner perspective that gives them depth.

The depicted bodies are entirely feasible as a 3D scene, and yet this composition is all about illusion. The hatch fill creates a perception of light. The dithering on the faces produces a sense of material texture. The squiggly lines imitate freehand drawing. The spatial perspective itself is achieved through a purely two-dimensional algorithm of polygon intersections and line hiding.

The original medium of my compositions is the pen plotter, and Traversal is no exception. It is entirely vector-based, and can be plotted directly. I use Paper.js to render it on-screen and as SVG.

~

To generate and download a plottable SVG file, press `S`. Please be patient; this process can take a while. The SVG can be plotted on an A5 paper. It contains two layers visible in Inkscape, so you can plot the light grey sketch lines with a different pen, or omit them altogether.

metadata.name: Efflorescence #9
metadata.description:
Efflorescence is a piece that bridges between Pouya and Fatima's hand crafted tiles and Gorilla Sun's generative work, and reflects their collective love for patterns and colour. Efflorescence is a generative token that creates unique compositions by random arrangement of different tiles and the colorisation thereof.

This generative token would not have been possible without Zeno Zeng's SVG runtime for P5JS!

Press the down arrow button to export an SVG of the artwork. In live view stroke width can be adjusted by zooming in and out.

metadata.name: Alienpillars #111
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: Speed of Dark #103
metadata.description:
Simple shapes, when strewn broadly and systematically, suggest the presence of infinite creative possibilities and are capable of portraying a visceral excitement felt by mixing the energy of light with the contemplation of dark.

This exercise has been repeated for ages, and its relevance will remain for as long as light may meet dark. The silhouettes of Stonehenge battling against a bright sky, the wabi-sabi placement of rocks in a Japanese garden hugged by methodical raking, the play of shadows in Plato's Allegory of the Cave, and the playfully arranged cut-outs of collage or chemical photogram — these all attest to the unending dynamism of form when imbued with light and the contrast of its absence.

As absence and darkness are made visible, the trail of their path conveys a speed as fast as light, and dark shapes that are no less important than the brightest figures. A symbiotic coexistence of these forces was born with the universe – and a delicate balance remains between the powerful glare of light and the stealthy speed of dark.

Inspired by photograms and a little-known series by documentary photographer William Klein, Speed of Dark references the visual language of the darkroom and the history of photography as an underlying analog for how an emerging art medium can harness simple elements to create evocative expressions.

Choose a resolution by adding "&width=9000" to the URL in live view.
Remove the border by adding "&noborder=1" to the URL.

__________
TENDER x Laurent Houdard
May 2022

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #164
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #411
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Seasons #161
metadata.description:
Seasons depicts monolithic mountains and calm seas scattered with unnatural elements.
The color palettes explore the colors of natural landscapes through different times of year.

To ease browser load, the images are paused by default.
Hitting 'p' will toggle a subtle animation.
Hitting 't' will toggle between the day and night palette for the image.
On mobile the resolution is reduced and the image is always paused to ease the load on the device.

Generative images by 0x3739
twitter.com/0x3739
library: twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library
license: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Tested and functioning correctly on Google Chrome version 100.0.4896.88 on Windows desktop and Android mobile device.

The work is rendered in webgl as a fragment shader.
Setting parameters in the javascript portion of the script generates a different fragment shader for each iteration.

Interactions
'-' to zoom in.
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'z' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to A4/A3/A2/A1 format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
'q' to change the aspect ratio to portrait.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
'p' to pause the animation the image.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the margins on the image.
'm' to toggle the mountains in the image.
'c' to toggle the clouds in the image.
'g' to toggle the grid in the image.
'd' to toggle the dirt speckles in the image.
'n' to toggle the noise in the image.
'j' to toggle the jitter in the image.
'v' to toggle all vintage effects in the image.
'1' to toggle the stars in the image.
'2' to toggle the moons in the image.
'3' to toggle the black squares in the image.
'4' to toggle the white squares in the image.
'5' to toggle the primary color squares in the image.
'6' to toggle the secundary color squares in the image.
'7' to toggle the colour correction in the image.
'8' to toggle the sea in the image.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash. 
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.
